<TEXT>
environmentalists and loggers are considering 
a proposal that would protect woods where the rare spotted owl lives 
but guarantee the timber industry could resume logging in other 
areas of the pacific northwest 
the proposal was made after a daylong meeting saturday attended 
by environmentalists timber industry representatives oregons 
congressional delegation and gov neil goldschmidt 
sen mark hatfield rore said at the beginning of the session 
that federal courts have blocked the harvest of 12 billion board 
feet of timber scheduled for harvest in oregon this year 
representing 28 percent of the annual harvest from federal lands in 
the state 
the courts have put off limits nearly a third of the federal 
lands usually open for logging in oregon and washington in response 
to lawsuits filed by environmentalists to save oldgrowth forests as 
spotted owl habitat 
the timber industry has estimated that 20000 jobs could be lost 
in oregon by 1991 if federal court injunctions restricting timber 
supply remain in force 
estimated to number fewer than 6000 in the northwest the 
spotted owl hunts and nests almost exclusively in oldgrowth forests 
that produce the logs most prized by the timber industry the bird 
also has been proposed as a threatened species by the us fish and 
wildlife service 
the proposal would guarantee the timber industry 8 billion board 
feet of timber from national forests in oregon and 1 billion board 
feet from bureau of land management forests over the next 15 months 
in return environmentalists would get legislation preserving 
significant oldgrowth stands and a commitment to adopt forest 
planning processes that minimize fragmentation of remaining stands 
once agreed to there would be no appeals of the type that have 
tied up timber on federal lands 
hatfield gave both sides until tuesday to decide whether to 
accept the proposal 
the meeting was the first time both sides in the 5yearold 
dispute have met 
i think what the delegation has done here is unprecedented 
said john hampton a timber company owner representing his industry 
at the summit i personally find the recommendation difficult to 
accept 
once again we find our industry asked to ramp down or reduce 
the timber base hampton said we never seem to ramp up 
thinking of the 90000 people who work in the timber industry 
i have to give it serious consideration he said 
art johnson a lawyer representing environmentalists at the 
meeting was even less encouraging 
there are a number of plaintiffs in the lawsuit he said 
we will respond as quickly as we can 
johnson repeated his suggestion to go to mediation to achieve 
agreement in the forest management dispute 
</TEXT>
