the interior department has come up with a 
specific dollar value for the thousands of birds mammals and other 
animals killed in the alaskan oil spill according to the washington 
post 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
it is the first time the rules have ever been applied to a 
largescale disaster such as the march 24 spill caused when the 
tanker exxon valdez hit a reef in prince william sound the 
newspaper reported in its monday editions 
for example each of the furry seals was worth 15 seagulls were 
worth 788 and canadian geese were worth 3574 each the 
newspaper reported striped bass were valued at 184 per pound 
the figures were developed from a computer model which is 
supposed to reflect the market value of the wildlife the post 
reported similar computer models will be used to determine a market 
value for the wildlife killed in three weekend oil spills in the 
waters off the continental united states the newspaper said 
the bill will eventually be sent to exxon owner of the tanker 
that spilled 11 million gallons of crude oil 
the damage assessment procedures have come under fire from 
environmentalists who argue that the rules dont account for the 
longterm damage to the environment the newspaper said 
thus far the oil has washed up on 728 miles of beaches and the 
dead wildlife count stands at 25700 migratory birds 800 sea 
otters 84 bald eagles and 20 harbor seals the post said 
but at this point it isnt yet even clear who will pay for the 
damage assessment the post said that is expected to take up to 
five years and cost 100 million but exxon has paid 15 million 
