<TEXT>
nuclear regulatory commission inspectors 
told three seabrook nuclear plant employees they should shut the 
reactor down before a plant operator belatedly responded nrc 
officials said 
but noel dudley who was present as senior nrc inspector at the 
plant denied previous allegations that nrc officials had to grab 
anyone to get a response as one prominent seabrook critic alleged 
us rep edward markey dmass said friday that he was told by 
commission officials including chairman lando zech that an nrc 
official grabbed a plant operator prior to thursdays unplanned 
shutdown 
the boston sunday globe reported details of the shutdown based on 
interviews with dudley plant officials and others the shutdown on 
the 10th day of lowpower tests at the 6 billion plant prompted 
the nrc to suspend further tests pending a thorough review 
plant officials said thursdays events began when a 
malfunctioning valve on the nonnuclear side of the plant produced 
changes in readouts from a component called a pressurizer on the 
nuclear side under plant procedures the change was sufficient to 
warrant a shutdown spokesman ron sher said sunday 
one nrc inspector and then dudley approached three different 
plant officials pointing out the problem but got no immediate 
results the globe said minutes later an operator did shut down 
the plant 
they were making a conscious decision to attempt to regain 
pressure control even though plant procedures called for a 
shutdown dudley said 
sher said the operator in charge chose to continue to monitor 
plant conditions because they were returning to the test condition 
several minutes later the operator recognized that the plant 
condition was still not within the parameters of the test procedure 
and then he shut the plant down 
the globe said an unidentified nrc inspector first approached 
seabrooks startup manager about the pressure reading when the 
manager did not respond the nrc inspector approached the test 
director who was closer to the scene in the control room and the 
director agreed the plant should be shut the paper said 
but the test director then talked to the shift supervisor a 
higherranking official who said that pressure was correcting on 
its own and that there was no need to turn off the plant the 
paper said 
dudley stepped in at that point approaching a still higher 
seabrook official the assistant operators manager the assistant 
manager consulted the operations manager who acknowledged the 
information and deferred to the decision of the shift supervisor to 
continue to operate nrc spokesman steve horwitz told the paper 
spokesmen have said neither the plant nor the public was 
endangered 
a decade behind schedule and 10 times over budget the bitterly 
contested plant won permission to conduct lowpower tests earlier 
this month delayed by one malfunction the tests began june 13 and 
had been running smoothly until the shutdown 
</TEXT>
