<TEXT>
at dawn each day two afghans haul two 
bags of hardboiled eggs sheep and calves liver nine miles to a 
kabul suburb 
basir amiri and ismail kazami are responsible for feeding 80000 
danish rainbow trout being bred in a swimming pool and eight canals 
in a former tourist resort 
the complex was closed a decade ago when moslem guerrillas 
launched their campaign to overthrow the prosoviet government 
the war not only has left 13 million people dead and forced at 
least 5 million into exile but also has created food shortages 
animal breeding has nearly come to a standstill poultry farms have 
closed and fields of many farms have been barren for years 
the fishbreeding project is one of several projects backed by 
the united nations in afghanistan the government took over the 
resort and last year turned over parts of it to the ministry of 
agriculture 
it is a humble effort we are trying to utilize whatever 
facilities we have to provide more protein to the afghans said 
hari dewan chief of the un food and agriculture organization 
which oversees the breeding project 
the afghans are basically redmeat eaters but we are trying to 
tell them to eat fish if and when available dewan said 
in march 1988 the fao flew 200000 frozen fish eggs from denmark 
within 36 hours hatched them in indoor wooden troughs at the resort 
and transferred them to the canals that are fed by nearby kargah 
lake eighty thousand have survived 
the trout were doing very well but soon there was a problem of 
space dewan said we asked the government to give us the unused 
swimming pool 
there are now about 50000 trout in the pool 
the afghans love meat and all main dishes are supposed to have a 
large portion even though meat is available in kabul home of 225 
million people the price is often too steep for most 
the government has frozen the price of nan the flat bread that 
is the main staple of the afghan diet at about six afghanis 10 
cents at the official exchange rate 
