<TEXT>
a suburban boston prosecutor says he will seek to 
charge hundreds of antiabortion demonstrations with a violation of 
the states civil rights act instead of merely with disorderly 
conduct 
norfolk county district attorney william delahunt said the new 
charges would represent the first time in massachusetts and probably 
in the nation that interfering with a womans right to an abortion 
would be interpreted as a civil rights violation 
he said he would drop disorderly conduct charges monday and file 
the civil rights charges which would have to be considered later by 
a grand jury 
civil rights violations can bring a jail term of up to a year and 
a fine of up to 1000 disorderly conduct is just a misdemeanor and 
rarely brings more than a relatively small fine 
delahunt said he hoped the prospect of stricter penalties will 
serve as a deterrent to antiabortion demonstrators 
we maintain a woman has a right to have an abortion he said 
saturday to be intimidated or coerced amounts to a violation 
of that right 
prolife activists who have staged demonstrations outside 
abortion clinics around the state and particularly in brookline 
during the past year said the possibility of being faced with a 
civil rights violation wouldnt deter protesters norfolk county 
includes brookline and other suburbs south of boston 
people feel so strongly about this that they will do whatever 
it costs to save lives said denise duda of mashpee who has been 
arrested along with her husband george in at least two 
antiabortion demonstrations i think it will be harder to prove a 
violation of civil rights 
delahunt said there were current charges against about 360 people 
arrested in antiabortion demonstrations 
he said he was basing his actions on a recent supreme judicial 
court ruling that limited the application of disorderly conduct laws 
in demonstrations 
the april 4 ruling involving a protest at falmouths otis air 
force base in 1986 said a demonstrator involved in a legitimate 
political protest could not be considered to have committed a 
criminal act under the disorderly conduct statute 
proceeding against hundreds of demonstrators on idle and 
disorderly conduct charges was not effective in the past delahunt 
said given their level of commitment its not effective for the 
future 
