a tropical depression in the gulf of mexico produced showers and 
thunderstorms sunday over parts of texas and showers and 
thunderstorms developed over the upper mississippi valley 
rain also fell along sections of the atlantic coast 
the tropical depression was drifting slowly northward producing 
tides up to 2 to 3 feet above normal along parts of the upper texas 
coast and the coast of louisiana showers and thunderstorms spread 
to southcentral and southeastern texas 
the highest sustained wind in the depression was around 35 mph 
with strengthening possible by midday monday if maximum sustained 
wind hit 39 mph it would be reclassified a tropical storm 
showers and thunderstorms developed along a warm front in the 
upper mississippi valley extending across eastern minnesota 
northeastern iowa and western wisconsin 
showers and thunderstorms developed over florida and along a 
stationary front curving through the atlantic coast a few showers 
and thunderstorms also developed along a frontal system curving 
through the lower great lakes region and northern ohio valley 
elsewhere a few showers spread over the northern rockies and the 
northern high plains 
rainfall reported during the six hours up to 2 pm edt were all 
less than an inch 
clouds and rain kept temperatures only in the 40s across parts of 
montana while the southern and eastern sections of the state 
enjoyed sunshine and readings in the 70s 
temperatures around the nation at 3 pm edt ranged from 47 
degrees at great falls mont to 100 at tucson ariz sundays low 
in the lower 48 states was 30 at west yellowstone mont 
