<TEXT>
gasoline prices across the nation dropped for 
the second time in four weeks according to a survey of retailers 
released sunday 
but an analyst who conducts the poll said new federal regulations 
will slow or stop the trend 
the bimonthly lundberg survey of 12000 gasoline stations 
concluded that average prices for all grades of gasoline and all 
types of service went down about a third of a penny to 11761 cents 
survey publisher trilby lundberg said sunday 
prices dropped twice as much earlier this month a june 9 survey 
concluded the survey released sunday covered a twoweek period 
which ended friday 
lundberg said the price dropped because refiners terminal 
operators and importers had stored an extra supply to meet the 
challenge of new federal environmental protection agency 
requirements 
the epa recently instituted new volatility standards for 
gasoline the idea is to have refiners make cleanerburning gasoline 
during summer months when sunlight cooks exhaust fumes into smog 
refiners had extra gasoline on hand in case they failed to meet 
the new regulations and had to refine additional batches but with 
successful compliance refiners found they had reserves available 
creating a surplus which lowered prices 
cleanerburning gasoline costs more to produce and the toughest 
standards are being imposed in july and august which also happens 
to be the peak holiday demand time for gasoline lundberg said 
in addition to the federal standards some states have adopted 
even stricter rules and refiners have begun referring to summer 
gasoline and winter gasoline lundberg said 
this price drop could be the last for a while said lundberg 
the rules are even tighter for july 1 than june 1 and it makes 
gasoline more costly to make 
according to the survey average prices per gallon at 
selfservice stations were regular unleaded 10779 cents premium 
unleaded 12322 cents and regular leaded 10724 cents 
at full service stations average prices were regular unleaded 
13293 cents premium unleaded 14464 cents regular leaded 13045 
cents 
all the grades of gasoline fell slightly from the previous 
survey lundberg said 
</TEXT>
